          h2
            |  Shop Application of Intumescent Fireproofing
          p
            |  Cementitious and intumescent are the two most commonly used fireproofing options in industrial settings. This article focuses on the process of applying intumescent fireproofing to structural steel in a shop setting. Fireproofing is designed to protect the structural integrity of steel under extreme fire conditions and to maintain certain temperatures for a specific amount of time. Intumescent fireproofing is used in refineries and petrochemical plants to protect the structural steel that supports high-risk or valuable equipment. Shop application of fireproofing is a 4-step process consisting of abrasive blasting, priming of the steel, applying the fireproofing, and adding a topcoat.
          h2 style="padding-top: 50px; font-size: 22px" Abrasive Blasting
          p
            | The first step in the fireproofing process is to abrasive blast the structural steel. Abrasive blasting, more commonly known as sandblasting, is when compressed air is used to push an abrasive media through a blasting nozzle to remove mill scale and contaminants and produce an anchor profile. Commonly used media for this application are steel grit, garnet, and coal slag. In a shop setting, steel grit is preferred because it can be reused, thus saving cost. Figure 1 shows carbon steel that has been blasted.
          h2 style="padding-top: 30px; font-size: 22px" Prime Coat
          p
            | Once surface contaminants have been removed, and an anchor profile has been established, the primer's first coat is applied. A typical primer for industrial use is an epoxy. The epoxy typically will be sprayed on and applied to reach the correct mils specified on the data page of the product being used. Manufacturers will select approved primers to be used under fireproofing. Such adequate adhesion can be achieved.

