          h2 style="padding-top: 30px; font-size: 22px" Fireproofing
          p
           | Following priming of the steel, a fire rating of 1.5 to 3 hours is usually specified. This means the steel can withstand heat for up to 1.5 to 3 hours. The fire rating is determined by how many miles of fireproofing is applied. Mils are best described as the thickness or amount of fireproofing added to the steel. Multiple coats of fireproofing are needed to reach maximum thickness. After applying one-third of the recommended fireproofing, a mesh material is required. The mesh acts in much the same way as rebar does with concrete. After the mesh is applied, the remaining two-thirds of the fireproofing is added. The fireproofing material can be either sprayed on or applied using a roller.
          h2 style="padding-top: 30px; font-size: 22px" Finish Coat
          p
           | A final topcoat is recommended over the fireproofed steel. If the structural steel is for exterior use, this will typically be a polyurethane paint. Polyurethane paints offer ultraviolet protection and resistance from external elements. If the structural steel is to be placed inside, then a polyurethane or epoxy is usually used.
          h2 style="padding-top: 30px; font-size: 22px" Loading and Unloading of Finished Steel
          p
           | Once everything is fireproofed, and a final coat has been applied, the steel must be shipped to its final destination. It is during this time that the fireproofed steel is most susceptible to damage. When unloading, it is crucial to place the fireproofed steel on the ground side by side. This is important because of the weight of steel. If placed on top of one another, or overlapped on the ground, stress fractures can occur. Disbondment is another problem that arises during unloading. This is often a case of oversight as the fireproofed steel is placed in a low area where water can form. If the fireproofed steel is put in an area where it can become submerged in water, the fireproofing will begin to pull away from the steel. Fireproofed steel needs to be placed in a dry area. In both cases, the damaged fireproofing must be completely removed down to bare steel. Once everything has been removed, the applicator must repeat the steps above to install fireproofing correctly.
          h2 style="padding-top: 30px; font-size: 22px" Block outs in the Field
          p
           | While most of the structural steel is fireproofed in a shop setting, some areas on the steel will need to be addressed in the field. For example, fireproofing is not performed on connection points in the shop because these areas need to be easily accessible for bolts and welding. In the field, these connections, known as block-outs, need to be prepared, primed, fireproofed, and top-coated in the same manner as the shop-applied fireproofing. Once assembled in place, the fireproofing can be applied over these areas to meet the specified fire rating. Fireproofing of steel is becoming increasingly common in refinery and petrochemical facilities. When exposed to extreme heat, nearly all structural steel loses its strength. Fireproofed coatings help both supports and statically loaded structures maintain their integrity longer. The application of intumescent fireproofing is a sophisticated process, requiring experienced staff and special equipment.